# Public Prosecutor _v_ Sinnathamby s/o Arumoh  

### \[2022\] SGDC 257

Criminal Law – Offences – Road Traffic Act – Drink Driving – Driver Sleeping in Stationary Vehicle – Not Driving at Time of Arrest

Criminal Law – Elements – Section 71A(1) Assumption – Section 71A(2) Requirements – Burden of Proof

3 November 2022 - Judgment reserved

### District Judge Sharmila Sripathy-Shanaz:

## Introduction

1       In the late hours of 4 February 2020, the Accused was found by the police while sleeping in a stationary lorry parked along a service road located near his place of residence. A breath evidential analyser test (“BEA”) revealed that his breath contained 44 microgrammes of alcohol in 100 millilitres of breath, which exceeded the prescribed limit.

2       The Accused has contested the charge of driving whilst under the influence of alcohol pursuant to s 67(1)(b) of the Road Traffic Act (“RTA”), contending that the excess alcohol in his breath was attributable to several cans of beer that he had consumed with a friend _after_ he had parked and ceased to drive his lorry.

3       Having heard the evidence and considered the submissions of the parties, this is my judgment.

## The Applicable Legal Principles

### The elements of an offence under s 67(1)(b)

4       An offence under s 67(1)(b) is established by the single fact that the proportion of alcohol in the offender’s body exceeds the prescribed limit in s 72(1) of the RTA: _Edwin s/o Suse Nathen v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2013\] 4 SLR 1139</span> at \[11\], _Stansilas Fabian Kester v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] 5 SLR 755</span> at \[34\].

5       In the context of the present case, the key elements of the offence are:

> a.     that the Accused had driven the lorry sometime between 9.00 p.m. and 10.00 p.m. on 4 February 2020 from Jalan Buroh to the service road at Block 445B Fernvale Road (“the service road”); and

> b.     that while driving the lorry, the proportion of alcohol in his breath exceeded the prescribed limit of 35 microgrammes in 100 millilitres of breath.[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1)

### The assumption under s 71A(1) RTA

6       To prove the second element, the Prosecution can rely on the assumption in s 71A(1) which provides that the proportion of alcohol in an offender’s breath at the time of the alleged offence shall be assumed to be not less than that in the specimen of breath provided by him.

7       As a threshold requirement, and before the s 71A(1) assumption can apply, it must first be shown that the offender had driven at the time of the alleged offence. Once the preliminary act has been proved, the assumption applies even if the offender was not driving at the time of his arrest. In other words, the offence does not abate just because the drink driver had ceased driving at the time of his arrest: _Public Prosecutor v Rangasamy Subramaniam_ <span class="citation">\[2011\] 1 SLR 767</span> (“_Rangasamy_”) at \[35\], \[41\] – \[42\], \[48\], \[53\], \[59\] and \[61\].

### The requirements to displace the assumption (s 71A(2) RTA)

8       Pursuant to s 71A(2), the assumption will be displaced if the offender proves, on a balance of probabilities, that:

> a.     he consumed alcohol after he had ceased to drive and before he provided the specimen (“the first limb”, commonly known as the defence of post-incident drinking); and

> b.     had he not done so, the proportion of alcohol in his breath would not have exceeded the prescribed limit (“the second limb”).

If _either_ limb is not satisfied, the assumption would operate and the offender would be guilty of drink driving.

9       Citing _DPP v Williams_ \[1989\] Crim LR 382, the Court of Appeal in _Rangasamy_ discussed how the assumption in s 71A(1) would operate (at \[57\]):

> In _Williams_, police officers found a car parked near an address where they found the respondent at around 4am. The respondent admitted that he had driven the car and said his last drink had been some five hours earlier. The respondent failed the breath test that was administered and was charged for drink-driving. The respondent submitted that by his imprecise admission of having driven that night he could have been indicating that he had driven before he drank and as such the Prosecution had not proven that at the time of driving the respondent was in excess of the prescribed limit. This was rejected by the High Court who held that **the respondent bore the burden of displacing the assumption that his breath/alcohol proportion had exceeded the statutory limit. Once he had admitted driving and once the specimen he gave showed that he was over the prescribed limit at the time of sampling, \[the UK equivalent to s 71A of the RTA\] operated to transfer the burden to the respondent.** Since that burden had not been discharged, the assumption applied and the respondent was guilty of drink driving.

(emphasis added)

10     In assessing the burden placed on an offender seeking to displace the assumption, regard may be had to _R v Drummond_ \[2002\] EWCA Crim 527 at \[31\],[\[note: 2\]](#Ftn_2) where the English Court of Appeal distilled the type of scientific evidence an offender can be expected to adduce to prove the second limb of s 71A(2):

> \[T\]he relevant scientific evidence to set against the result ascertained from the specimen of breath or blood is all within the knowledge (or means of access) of the accused rather than the Crown. This evidence will include:

>> (1)    the amount which the accused had to drink after the accident;

>> (2)    what is called \[the accused’s\] “blood-breath ratio”, important for calculating the rate at which his body absorbs alcohol;

>> (3)    the rate at which \[the accused’s\] body eliminates alcohol over time;

>> (4)    the accused’s body weight.

11     The burden on the offender is an onerous one and while the Court has a discretion to find the assumption discharged _without_ expert evidence, this is only in rare cases where a layman could reliably and confidently say that the alcohol consumed after the offender had stopped driving, explained the excess alcohol found in his breath. Where the latter is not obvious to a layman, it remains necessary for the offender to call expert evidence in order to discharge the onus of proof which rests upon him: _DPP v Dukolli_ \[2009\] EWHC 3097, _Pugsley v Hunter_ \[1973\] RTR 284. Such evidence would enable the Court to ascertain if the BEA test result is consistent with the offender’s account of post-incident drinking.

## The Key Issues for Determination

12     In the present case, the Accused does not dispute the first element of the charge, _viz._ that he had driven his lorry sometime between 9.00 p.m. and 10.00 p.m. on 4 February 2020 from Jalan Buroh to the service road. He also does not dispute the BEA test result disclosing that the proportion of alcohol in his breath at 2.23 a.m. on 5 February 2020 was 44 microgrammes per 100 millilitres of breath and thus exceeded the prescribed limit.

13     Therefore, the second element, _viz._ whether the proportion of alcohol in the Accused’s breath exceeded the prescribed limit at the time that he drove the lorry, is the primary issue for determination in this case.

14     Allied to this, and given the Prosecution’s reliance on the assumption in s 71A(1) to prove the second element,[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3) are the secondary issues of:

> a.     whether, as asserted by the Accused, he had consumed alcohol after he had ceased to drive and before he provided the specimen; and

> b.     if so, whether the proportion of alcohol in his breath would not have exceeded the prescribed limit but for this consumption.

15     For the Accused’s benefit since he is a litigant-in-person, I also address (albeit briefly since the law on this issue is clear) his contention that he is not guilty of the offence as he had not been driving and was merely resting in his vehicle at the time of his arrest.[\[note: 4\]](#Ftn_4)

16     I examine these issues in due course, but turn first, to summarize the evidence led by the respective parties.

## The Prosecution’s Case

17     The facts, according to the various Prosecution witnesses, are as follows.

### The first information report

18     At about 10.54 p.m. on 4 February 2020, the police received a telephone call from Mr Ngo Kwang Hock (“Mr Ngo”) who reported a possible drunk driver.[\[note: 5\]](#Ftn_5) Mr Ngo had sought police assistance after hearing three long _“dragging”_ horns from a lorry parked along the service road, over the span of about 90 minutes; from about 9.00 p.m. to sometime after 10.00 p.m.[^6] After the second horn, Mr Ngo observed someone lying across the seats in the lorry with his head resting on the passenger seat and his leg near the steering wheel.[^7]

### Investigations at the scene

19     Sergeant Md Ridwan Bin Abdullah (“Sgt Ridwan”) and Senior Staff Sergeant Noreffendi Bin Othman (“SSSgt Noreffendi”) were despatched to the scene and arrived at about 11.24 p.m.[\[note: 8\]](#Ftn_8) to find the Accused asleep, slumped over the steering wheel[^9] in the driver’s seat of a stationary lorry bearing registration number YP 8295H (“the lorry”). The driver’s door was ajar, the engine was not running, the headlights were switched off and the hazard lights were on.[^10] The officers took photographs of the scene[^11] before approaching the Accused. After several unsuccessful attempts at rousing him by shaking his shoulder, the Accused awoke and, in response to the officers’ preliminary queries, stated that he had been resting in his lorry as he resided in the vicinity. He was observed to be drowsy with slurred speech and had _“alcoholic breath”_. When asked if he had consumed any alcohol, the Accused informed the officers that he had drunk a can of beer at his workplace in Jalan Buroh.[^12] He also informed the officers that he had neither alighted from the lorry nor consumed any alcohol _after_ parking at the service road.[^13]

20     Based on their observations of the Accused, the officers decided to conduct a formal interview. Guided by Exhibit P2 (also referred to interchangeably in the notes of evidence as the proforma), a series of questions were posed to the Accused and his responses duly recorded.[\[note: 14\]](#Ftn_14) SSSgt Noreffendi testified that he penned down the exact answer given to each question. When the Accused could not provide an answer, the question would be left blank.[^15]

21     For ease of reference, the salient parts of Exhibit P2 are reproduced. In the proforma, the Accused stated that he had consumed one can of beer and had thereafter driven from his workplace at Jalan Buroh to the incident location:

![](data:image;base64,)

22     He denied consuming alcoholic beverages after stopping his vehicle:

![](data:image;base64,)

23     As the Accused was unable to provide an answer when asked _who_ he had consumed alcohol with, the question was left blank.[\[note: 16\]](#Ftn_16) A trial, the officers testified that the Accused _“did not mention drinking with anyone else”_ after parking his lorry.[^17]

24     At about 12.15 a.m. on 5 February 2022, after Exhibit P2 had been completed, Sgt Ridwan conducted a handheld breathalyzer test (“preliminary breath test”). The Accused failed the test.[\[note: 18\]](#Ftn_18) Acting on the instructions of Investigating Officer Norashikin Bte Daud (“IO Norashikin”), the officers informed him that he would be placed under arrest for an offence of being in charge of a vehicle under the influence of drink.[^19] Exhibit P2 was then shown to the Accused, and the questions and answers were read back to him.[^20] He became uncooperative only when invited to append his signature on Exhibit P2, and began protesting loudly that the police were being _“unfair”_ as _“he wasn’t driving at that point of time when \[the police had\] caught up with him”_[^21] and had travelled _“very slowly from Jalan Buroh”_ to the incident location.[^22]

25     Having heard the commotion, the Accused’s friend, Mr Saravanan s/o Vaithanatasam (“Mr Saravanan”) and his wife arrived at the scene. Mr Saravanan introduced himself as the Accused’s cousin.[\[note: 23\]](#Ftn_23) At trial, both Sgt Ridwan and SSSgt Noreffendi testified that Mr Saravanan did _not_ make any mention of having drunk alcohol with the Accused earlier.[^24]

26     After reading Exhibit P2,[\[note: 25\]](#Ftn_25) Mr Saravanan spoke to the Accused to defuse situation. He also advised the Accused to calm down and cooperate with the police.[^26] Heeding Mr Saravanan’s advice, the Accused voluntarily appended his signature on Exhibit P2. He was then placed under arrest and escorted to Traffic Police Headquarters by Station Inspector How Kit Seng (“SI How”) and Sergeant Ameer Hamzah Bin Zailani (“Sgt Ameer”) who had arrived at the scene to assist. Mr Saravanan was given custody of the lorry as the police did not require it for investigations[^27] and there was nothing incriminating found in it.[^28]

### The BEA test

27     At about 2.19 a.m., Staff Sergeant Faezah Bte Mohamad Ata (“SSgt Faezah”) conducted a BEA test on the Accused, and his breath specimen was found to contain 44 microgrammes of alcohol in 100 millilitres of breath.[\[note: 29\]](#Ftn_29)

### The long statement

28     At about 3.05 a.m., IO Norashikin recorded a statement from the Accused after informing him that he had failed the BEA test as the alcohol content in his breath specimen exceeded the prescribed limit. The statement was recorded in English and neither IO Norashikin nor the Accused had any difficulty communicating with, and/or understanding, each other. The Accused was _“very calm”_ throughout the process and did not raise any complaints. The only query he had, pertained to the arrest warrant against him for breaching a personal protection order that his wife had obtained.[\[note: 30\]](#Ftn_30)

29     In the statement, admitted as Exhibit P4 without any challenge to its voluntariness, the Accused states as follows (reproduced below in verbatim and uncorrected):

> 2    On the 4th February 2020 at about 9.00 plus pm, I was at my work place which is located at Jalan Buruh. There, I admitted to consume one can of “Tiger” Beer alone. I finished drinking about fifteen minutes later. I then drove my lorry, YP8295H, alone; with the intention to head (home)[\[note: 31\]](#Ftn_31). I then arrived at my car park, which is located at Blk 447 Jalan Kayu. I did not park at the designated parking lot but I on the hazard light. **I off my engine and then rested at the driver’s seat. I wished to state that I did not consume any alcohol after I left my work place.**

> 3    While I was sleeping, the police came. I woke up and was being interviewed. I admitted to the police office that I had consumed alcohol earlier and was just resting in the vehicle. The police officer then administered a breathalyzer test on me and I failed. I was arrested and then escorted to Traffic Police Station and asked to perform another test using a bigger machine (BAD). I completed the test with one attempt and the reading shows 44µg/100ml. I acknowledged and signed on the slip and was given a copy.

> \[…\]

> Q5:    Anything else you wish to add on?

> A5:     **I reached my car park safely, off the engine and took off the keys. I did on my hazard light. I just wanted to rest in my lorry when the police officer came**.

(emphasis added)

30     At trial, IO Norashikin testified that no claim of post-incident drinking was raised by the Accused during the recording of Exhibit P4.[\[note: 32\]](#Ftn_32)

### The cautioned statement

31     At about 4.00 a.m., IO Norashikin recorded a cautioned statement from the Accused; tendered in evidence as Exhibit P5 without any challenge as to its voluntariness. IO Norashikin testified that the Accused similarly did not mention anything about post-incident drinking during the recording of this statement.[\[note: 33\]](#Ftn_33) Instead, when invited to state his defence to the charge of drink driving, the Accused _personally handwrote_[^34] the following (reproduced below in verbatim and uncorrected):

> **Once i reach home, (carpark)[^35] I had no intention to drink any further. I parked my vehicle switched off my engine and rested** with my hazard lights on. **I was sleeping inside my vehicle for more than an hour until the police came** to wake me up. I **regret my mistake** and **pleading for leniency**. This is my only salary i have to survive, to earn a living for my family.

(emphasis added)

32     Recording of Exhibit P5 concluded at about 4.10 a.m., with the Accused voluntarily appending his signature on each page of the document.

### The previous conviction

33     The Prosecution closed its case with the evidence of the current Investigating Officer Yus Mastari Khazali (“IO Yus Mastari”) who tendered Exhibit P9-1 which disclosed that the Accused was, on 2 February 2005, convicted and sentenced under s 67(1)(b) of the RTA for driving a vehicle when the proportion of alcohol in the body exceeded the prescribed limit.

## The Defence’s Case

34     The Accused testified and called his wife (Ms Rathiga De Hanabell (“Ms Rathiga”)) and Mr Saravanan to give evidence on his behalf. In essence, the Accused’s defence was one of post-incident drinking.

### The Accused’s evidence

35     The Accused’s evidence, as gleaned from both his testimony and cross-examination of the Prosecution witnesses, is summarized below.

36     On the night of 4 February 2020, the Accused drank one can of beer at his workplace prior to driving home.[\[note: 36\]](#Ftn_36) Sometime between 8.00 p.m. and 9.00 p.m., he parked at the service road (adjacent to the block of flats where he resided) and was on his way to the supermarket on foot when he met Mr Saravanan who invited him for a drink. The Accused agreed and proceeded to a coffeeshop in the vicinity where he drank approximately three cans of 330ml Tiger Beer which Mr Saravanan had taken from his car.[^37]

37     Subsequently, the Accused was returning home on foot when he had an argument with his wife over a telephone call. He decided not to return home that night as he did not want the fight to escalate, and thus proceeded to sleep in his parked lorry only to be awoken by police officers at about 11.00 p.m.[\[note: 38\]](#Ftn_38) Under cross-examination, the Accused accepted that he had not been roused by the long horns that had resulted when he unwittingly lay on the horn whilst asleep in the lorry.[^39]

38     The Accused testified that he had told police officers at the scene that he had been drinking at the coffee shop. He also claimed to have told the police officers _who_ he had consumed alcohol with during the recording of Exhibit P2, but could not account for why the relevant section in the document had been left blank.[\[note: 40\]](#Ftn_40) He further claimed to have told the police officers that he had consumed alcoholic beverages after parking the lorry but asserted that they had failed to reflect this in Exhibit P2.[^41]

39     According to the Accused, the police officers at the scene were not interested in what he had to say and insisted that he take a breathalyzer test. He agreed, and testified that once he failed the test, _“nobody wanted to listen to anything that \[he had to\] say”_ and they just _“wanted \[him\] to go to the station to tell the IO what \[had\] happened.”_[\[note: 42\]](#Ftn_42) He stated that he had signed Exhibit P2 as he was under the impression that it was _“good for \[him\]”_.[^43] In the course of cross-examining Sgt Ridwan and SSSgt Noreffendi, the Defence also alleged that the police officers had ignored Mr Saravanan and warned him not to interfere in police matters when he told them that he had been drinking with the Accused.[^44]

40     Under cross-examination, the Accused accepted that Sgt Ridwan and SSSgt Noreffendi had no reason to implicate him or omit to state something which he had told them, in Exhibit P2.[\[note: 45\]](#Ftn_45)

41     In respect of Exhibit P4 (his long statement), the Accused accepted that he had told IO Norashikin that he had _not_ consumed any alcohol after leaving his workplace.[\[note: 46\]](#Ftn_46) However, he testified that Exhibit P4 did not contain _“some information”_ as IO Norashikin had told him not to tell her anything and to tell the judge in Court, what had happened.[^47] In a similar vein, while the Accused accepted that he had handwritten the words in Exhibit P5 (his cautioned statement), he claimed not to have stated his defence because IO Norashikin had informed him that _“she \[did not\] want to listen to anything.”_[^48]

### Mr Saravanan’s evidence

42     Mr Saravanan testified that he had drunk with the Accused on the night of 4 February 2020. However, he could not recall how much or what the Accused drank,[\[note: 49\]](#Ftn_49) what time they drank[^50] or how long they drank.[^51] Mr Saravanan also could state where they drank, save for vaguely alluding to having done so _“near the coffeeshop … not exactly at the coffeeshop.”_[^52]

43     Sometime after parting ways with the Accused, Mr Saravanan was at home when he heard a commotion and observed his friend arguing with some police officers.[\[note: 53\]](#Ftn_53) He thus proceeded to the service road with his wife. Mr Saravanan spoke to the Accused at the scene but was unable to recall what they had discussed.[^54] He also could not remember whether he had told police officers at the scene, that he had drunk with the Accused earlier that night.

44     Under cross-examination, Mr Saravanan conceded that though he knew the Accused was under investigation for drink driving several days later when he was released on bail,[\[note: 55\]](#Ftn_55) he had not gone to the police to inform them that he had drunk with his friend on the night of 4 February 2020.[^56]

### Ms Rathiga’s evidence

45     Ms Rathiga testified that she had argued with the Accused over a telephone call on the night of 4 February 2020. When she next spoke to him, he was already at the police station.[\[note: 57\]](#Ftn_57)

## The Court’s Findings

46     I turn now to examine _in seriatim_, the issues in contention (_supra_ at \[13\] to \[15\]).

47     Since there is no dispute that the Accused was driving at the time of the alleged offence, and the specimen he gave shows that he was over the prescribed limit at the time of sampling, s 71A(1) operates to transfer the burden to him to show, on the balance of probabilities, that: (i) he had consumed alcohol after he ceased to drive and before his breath specimen; and (ii) the proportion of alcohol in his breath would not have exceeded the prescribed limit but for his post-incident drinking.

48     I would state at the outset that I do _not_ find _either_ of the aforesaid limbs (which are relevant to my determination of whether the Accused has successfully availed himself of s 71A(2)) to be satisfied.

### Accused failed to show that he drank alcohol after driving

49     For the reasons that follow, I find that the objective evidence before this Court simply does not cohere with a finding that the Accused had consumed alcohol with Mr Saravanan after he had ceased to drive.

50     Foremost, the cogency of this defence is significantly undermined by the inconsistent (and incompatible) narratives proffered by the Accused. Notably, I find not an iota of evidence in the three statements recorded during investigations, to substantiate his claim that he had consumed _any_ alcohol _after_ driving:

> (a)     in the proforma (Exhibit P2), recorded at the scene, the Accused _expressly denied_ having consumed alcoholic beverages after stopping his vehicle (_supra_ at \[20\]). When asked who he had consumed alcohol with, the Accused offered no response and made no mention of his (purported) interaction with Mr Saravanan (_supra_ at \[21\]). Under cross-examination, the Accused himself agreed that Exhibit P2 makes no mention of any post-incident drinking;[\[note: 58\]](#Ftn_58)

> (b)     in his long statement (Exhibit P4) recorded several hours after his arrest, the Accused categorically stated that _he “did not consume any alcohol after \[he\] left \[his\] work place”_ and had merely parked the lorry upon reaching the service road, turned off the engine, turned on the hazard lights, removed the keys and rested until the police officers approached him (_supra_ at \[27\] – \[28\]). Nothing in Exhibit P4 suggests that the Accused had consumed alcohol after he had parked his vehicle; and

> (c)     in his cautioned statement (Exhibit P5; _supra_ at \[29\]) recorded after being warned of the consequences of not stating his defence, the Accused stated that he had no intention of drinking further upon reaching the service road. He similarly reiterated that he had parked the lorry, switched off the engine and had been resting inside the vehicle for more than an hour when he was awoken by the police officers. The Accused also expressed regret for his _“mistake”_ and pled for leniency.

51     I would observe that the Accused’s _multiple express admissions_ in Exhibits P2, P4, and P5 that he had done no more than sleep in the lorry upon reaching the service road, stands in stark contrast to his claim at trial, of post-incident drinking with Mr Saravanan.

52     Not unexpectedly, the Accused attempted to explain away these glaring material omissions by alleging that the police officers had refused to listen to him when he told them that he had drunk alcohol with Mr Saravanan at a coffeeshop in the vicinity of the incident location.[\[note: 59\]](#Ftn_59) This assertion was unequivocally rejected by the police officers:

> (a)     Sgt Ridwan and SSSgt Noreffendi steadfastly maintained that the Accused did not mention having drunk three cans of beer with Mr Saravanan, after parking his lorry at the service road (_supra_ at \[21\]);[\[note: 60\]](#Ftn_60)

> (b)     on the contrary, both officers testified that the Accused had informed them that he had only consumed one can of beer at his workplace in Jalan Buroh.[\[note: 61\]](#Ftn_61) He also informed the officers that he did not go anywhere after parking his lorry along the service road and had remained in the vehicle to rest.[^62] According to the officers, the Accused’s _only_ protest during the recording of Exhibit P2, centered on his belief that he could not be arrested for drink-driving because he had not been stopped by Traffic Police officers while driving his vehicle from Jalan Buroh to Fernvale Road (_supra_ at \[22\]);[^63]

> (c)     SSSgt Noreffendi testified that he had faithfully documented everything that the Accused had said to him during the recording of Exhibit P2. He also explained that several sections were left blank when no answer was proffered by the Accused;[\[note: 64\]](#Ftn_64)

> (d)     IO Norashikin testified that Exhibit P4 documented everything that the Accused had told her[\[note: 65\]](#Ftn_65) and he had not mentioned any post-incident drinking with Mr Saravanan;[^66] and

> (e)     IO Norashikin similarly gave evidence that the Accused had made no claim of post-incident drinking during the recording of Exhibit P5.[\[note: 67\]](#Ftn_67)

53     In assessing the veracity of the police officers’ evidence, I am mindful that none of them have any reason to falsely implicate the Accused or mislead the Court; a fact that the Accused himself accepted under cross-examination.[\[note: 68\]](#Ftn_68) Furthermore, the police officers provided consistent and cogent evidence and I have no reason (especially in the absence of one proffered by the Defence) to doubt their credibility.

54     Juxtaposed against this, are the Accused’s dubious claims which have evolved at trial materially, without a satisfactory explanation. To this end, I would observe that the Accused’s failure to provide a cogent reason for omitting to state his defence of post-incident drinking in _any_ of the three statements, particularly in Exhibit P5 where he was given the opportunity to write, unrestrained, whatever he wished to with the pen and paper _handed to him_,[\[note: 69\]](#Ftn_69) further undermines his case and his credibility. This is especially since, having understood the Notice of Warning administered to him during the recording of Exhibit P5, he wrote an otherwise detailed and clearly considered defence to the charge of drink driving and even made an amendment to the statement prior to signing it.[^70] The Accused’s defence is further hampered by the fact that his allegations of police impropriety only arose at trial and cannot be reconciled with the fact that (despite claiming that the officers’ failure to include his defence in Exhibits P2, P4 and P5 amounted to a grave injustice) he failed to avail himself of obvious avenues of recourse to address the purported wrongs against him.[^71]

55     In my assessment, the evidence of the three police officers is mutually corroborative and, when considered alongside the objective evidence before this Court (_supra_ at \[50\] and \[52\]), incontrovertibly establishes that the Accused did _not_ (throughout investigations) raise the fact of post-incident drinking, _despite_ having had _three distinct opportunities_ to do so. This inexplicable belatedness ultimately proves fatal as it suggests that the defence is but an ill-conceived afterthought.[\[note: 72\]](#Ftn_72)

56     Second, the aforesaid finding is in fact buttressed by the fact that the Accused’s admission in Exhibit P5, _viz._ that he had arrived at the service road and fallen asleep in his parked lorry for _“more than an hour”_, is consistent with Mr Ngo’s unchallenged evidence that he heard three long horns from the lorry over the span of about 90 minutes from about 9.00 p.m. to sometime after 10.00 p.m.,[\[note: 73\]](#Ftn_73) and had seen someone lying across the seats in the lorry after the second horn.[^74] Mr Ngo’s evidence would suggest that the Accused had in fact been resting in the lorry throughout this period and had not, as he otherwise contended in Court, been imbibing alcohol at a nearby coffeeshop. Mr Ngo’s evidence thus cohered with the Accused’s admission in Exhibit P5, which in turn squarely contradicted the defence run at trial.

57     Third, I find it unsafe to rely on Mr Saravanan’s evidence as corroboration of the defence. In assessing the cogency of Mr Saravanan’s evidence and the weight to be accorded to it, I am mindful that the duo are friends known to each other for at least six years, who meet not infrequently.[\[note: 75\]](#Ftn_75) Mr Saravanan cannot therefore be said to be a neutral or disinterested party and I am very much alive to the possibility that he may, on account of his continuing friendship with the Accused, have sought to provide evidence favorable to him. It is thus incumbent upon me to scrutinize his evidence before ascribing any weight to it.

58     To this end, I would make the following observations:

> (a)     Mr Saravanan’s _purported_ inability to recall key details of his alleged drinking session with the Accused on the night of 4 February 2020 (_viz._ what time they drank, what they drank and how much they drank), renders his account wholly deficient and tenuous;

> (b)     The cogency of Mr Saravanan’s evidence is further undermined by the curious belatedness of his claims – at the scene, he did not inform police officers that he had been drinking with the Accused,[\[note: 76\]](#Ftn_76) he also did not come forward as a witness in the days’ after the Accused’s release on bail (or at any juncture prior to the trial), despite (i) knowing that the latter had been accused of drink driving[^77] and (ii) agreeing that it would have been only natural for him to have wanted to provide the police with information that could assist his friend;[^78] and

> (c)     Mr Saravanan’s credibility is further shaken by the fact that the police officers roundly rejected his assertion that he had told them he could not take control of the lorry because he had been drinking.[\[note: 79\]](#Ftn_79)

59     The aforementioned factors coalesce to cast a spectre of doubt over the veracity of Mr Saravanan’s evidence. I thus find it unsafe to rely on his evidence as corroboration of the defence. I must stress that this finding is not premised solely on the fact that Mr Saravanan and the Accused are friends. Rather, it is a confluence of the factors canvassed above, that lead me to this conclusion. The consequence of my finding is that the defence remains uncorroborated.

60     Finally, for completeness, I would highlight that I find nothing in Ms Rathiga’s evidence that would assist the Accused’s case. Since she was not privy to how much alcohol her husband had consumed nor when he had done so, her evidence was of no utility to the Defence.

61     In sum, for the reasons at \[48\] to \[57\], I find that the evidence before this Court simply does not cohere with a finding that the Accused had consumed alcohol with Mr Saravanan after he had ceased to drive. The Defence’s failure to satisfy the first limb of s 71A(2) is fatal to displacing the assumption in s 71A(1). For completeness however, I turn briefly to address the second limb.

### No evidence of post-incident alcohol consumption that put the Accused over the limit

62     In considering the merits of the second limb, I note that _no evidence_ was led by the Defence to establish that the proportion of alcohol in the Accused’s breath would _not_ have exceeded the prescribed limit had he _not_ consumed alcohol after parking at the service road.

63     The Court requires expert evidence to weigh the factors, distilled as relevant, at \[10\] above. Thus, even _if_ (in spite of the foregoing analysis at \[59\]), I accept that the Accused had consumed alcohol after parking at the service road, I am nonetheless constrained to find that he has failed to show, on a balance of probabilities, that had he not consumed the post-incident alcohol, the proportion of alcohol in his breath would not have exceeded the prescribed limit.

### It is immaterial that the Accused was not driving at the time of his arrest

64     Finally, I address the Accused’s contention, both at the time of his arrest and at trial, that he cannot be found guilty of the offence as he was merely resting in his vehicle at the time of his arrest. It is a settled principle of law that an offence of drinking driving does not abate just because the drink driver had, for some reason, ceased driving at the time of his arrest (_supra_ at \[7\]).

65     The Court of Appeal’s observations in _Rangasamy_, squarely address the Accused’s assertion in the following terms (at \[42\]):

> \[s\] 67 of the RTA plainly states that any person who, when driving or attempting to drive a motor vehicle on a road or other public place, had so much alcohol in his body that the proportion of it in his breath exceeded the prescribed limit shall be guilty of an offence. **There is nothing in that particular provision to suggest that the offence abates just because the drink driver stops after a particular point of time.** Certainly, **nothing in the Parliamentary Debates … as well as the relevant provisions suggest that those who drive with excess alcohol could necessarily escape punishment just because there was a lapse of time between the commission of the offence and the arrest.**

(emphasis added)

### The finding of guilt

66     In satisfying neither limb in s 71A(2), the Accused has failed to displace the assumption in s 71A(1). The Court must thus assume that the proportion of alcohol in the Accused’s breath at the time of the offence was not less than that in the specimen of breath procured from him for the BEA test, _viz._ 44 microgrammes per 100 millilitres of breath. As this is over the prescribed limit, I find the Accused guilty of drink-driving and convict him accordingly.

67     I will now hear parties’ submissions on sentence.
